05275nam a22006975i 9780824861063DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20112011hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248610637 a10.1515/97808248610632doi  a(DE-B1597)484428  a(OCoLC)794925364  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0480002bisacsh0483pa305.42qDE-1011 aIkeya, Chie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRefiguring Women, Colonialism, and Modernity in Burma /cChie Ikeya. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b26 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSoutheast Asia: Politics, Meaning, and Memory ;v5500tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Colonial Setting -- t2 Women on the Rise -- t3 Between Patriotism and Feminism -- t4 Modern Woman as Consumer -- t5 Mixing Religion and Race -- t6 The Self-Indulgent Khit hsan thu -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Frequently Used Burmese Terms -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRefiguring Women, Colonialism, and Modernity in Burma presents the first study of one of the most prevalent and critical topics of public discourse in colonial Burma: the woman of the khit kala—"the woman of the times"—who burst onto the covers and pages of novels, newspapers, and advertisements in the 1920s. Educated and politicized, earner and consumer, "Burmese" and "Westernized," she embodied the possibilities and challenges of the modern era, as well as the hopes and fears it evoked. In Refiguring Women, Chie Ikeya interrogates what these shifting and competing images of the feminine reveal about the experience of modernity in colonial Burma. She marshals a wide range of hitherto unexamined Burmese language sources to analyze both the discursive figurations of the woman of the khit kala and the choices and actions of actual women who—whether pursuing higher education, becoming political, or adopting new clothes and hairstyles—unsettled existing norms and contributed to making the woman of the khit kala the privileged idiom for debating colonialism, modernization, and nationalism.The first book-length social history of Burma to utilize gender as a category of sustained analysis, Refiguring Women challenges the reigning nationalist and anticolonial historical narratives of a conceptually and institutionally monolithic colonial modernity that made inevitable the rise of ethnonationalism and xenophobia in Burma. The study demonstrates the irreducible heterogeneity of the colonial encounter and draws attention to the conjoined development of cosmopolitanism and nationalism. Ikeya illuminates the important roles that Burmese men and women played as cultural brokers and agents of modernity. She shows how their complex engagements with social reform, feminism, anticolonialism, media, and consumerism rearticulated the boundaries of belonging and foreignness in religious, racial, and ethnic terms. Refiguring Women adds significantly to examinations of gender and race relations, modernization, and nationalism in colonized regions. It will be of interest to a broad audience—not least those working in the fields of Southeast Asian studies, colonial and postcolonial studies, cultural studies, and women’s and gender studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSex rolezBurma. 0aWomenzBurmaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzBurmaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package